[Epuyen is located in the Andes mountains, and the virus most likely involved, although not stated, is Andes hantavirus, which is endemic in the southern Andes. This is the beginning of the summer season, when cases of hantavirus infection occur. The group quoted above states that they hypothesize that the outbreak is due to human-to-human transmission, which would be unusual. Andes virus is rarely transmitted directly person to person and only through close physical contact, usually within the family. No mention is made above of close relationships among these cases. The most common source of the infection is the long-tailed pygmy rice rat. The patients likely came into contact with areas inhabited by the rodent reservoir of the virus in the region. A comparison of the RNA sequences of the viruses in these cases may provide interesting additional information, as would any sequences of the viruses in the rodent hosts present in the localities where the cases occurred.

Images of the long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_), the Sigmodontine rodent host of Andes hantavirus, can be seen at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligoryzomys_longicaudatus#/media/File:Raton_colilarga.jpg. - Mod.TY

